# JWT Profile for Agent Identity and Entitlement in OAuth 2.0 Token Exchange Actor Tokens

draft-hyland-oauth-agent-actor-token-04

## Abstract

This specification profiles the `actor_token` parameter of OAuth 2.0 Token Exchange [RFC8693] to carry, in delegated agentic flows, the identity of a software agent acting on behalf of a Principal and an optional entitlement constraint on that agent. It defines two JSON Web Token (JWT) claims for use in the `actor_token`: `aid` (a reference to a named profile in the agent operator’s client metadata) and `ent` (an inline entitlement). The `aid` and `ent` claims are mutually exclusive. It also defines one entity metadata member for the agent operator’s OAuth client, `entitlement_profiles`, by which the agent operator declares the named profiles its agents may reference; a referenced profile MAY carry an entitlement constraint or MAY identify the agent with no entitlement constraint at all.

The profile applies only to Token Exchange requests in which both `subject_token` and `actor_token` are present (delegation semantics per [RFC8693] Section 1.1). Operational attribution of the agent (the deployment that launched it and the human operator of record) was specified in an earlier revision of this document; it has been removed and is delegated to a companion profile of [RFC7523] client assertions, so that workload-domain and operator information does not propagate along the token-exchange chain. See Section 1.3.

