## 5. Policy

### 5.1. Inputs to the Policy Decision

After processing per Section 4, the AS has available:

- the Token Exchange request parameters (`scope`, `resource`, `audience`, request-level `authorization_details`, etc.);
- the validated subject_token (the Principal — handled by [RFC8693], unmodified here);
- the validated actor_token: the agent operator (`iss`) and agent (`sub`) identifiers, and the validated agent entitlement, if any (the constraint from the profile named by `aid`, the validated `ent` object, or nothing);
- local policy.

### 5.2. The Validated Agent Entitlement as a Ceiling

When the AS has a validated agent entitlement, it is a **ceiling on the issued token’s authority over resources**, applied at delegation processing time. It is not itself a grant. The effective issued authority SHALL be the intersection of:

- the validated agent entitlement (the profile’s declared constraint, or the validated `ent`);
- the client’s requested authority (request parameters);
- any further narrowing by AS policy.

Authority is never broadened by any input; each can only narrow. If the actor_token carries neither `aid` nor `ent`, or carries an `aid` naming an entitlement-free profile, this profile imposes no agent-entitlement ceiling — issuance proceeds under [RFC8693] and AS local policy (Section 5.5).

### 5.3. Reflection into the Issued Token’s `act` Claim

Per [RFC8693] Section 4.1, the actor_token’s identity claims flow into the issued token’s `act` claim. This profile permits, but does not require, the AS to additionally reflect the agent entitlement into `act`:

- The AS MAY include `aid` or `ent` in the issued token’s `act` claim, making the agent’s entitlement visible to the resource server, which can apply it at the resource boundary. This is the enforcement fallback for cases where the AS cannot itself fully enforce the entitlement.

Whether to reflect, and which form, is a deployment decision; AS policy SHOULD consider enforcement coverage (Section 8.7), disclosure of concrete values (`ent`) versus profile name only (`aid`) (Section 8.4), and issued-token size. Reflection follows the [RFC8693] Section 4.1 rules: reflected `aid`/`ent` are identity-scoped descriptive members within `act`, alongside the standard `sub` and `iss`, and are not independent grants (Section 1.2).

### 5.4. Error Conditions

Where the actor_token carries `aid` or `ent`, this profile aligns its error behaviour with OAuth 2.0 Rich Authorization Requests [RFC9396] Section 5, treating an unacceptable or malformed agent entitlement the way the token endpoint treats an unacceptable or malformed `authorization_details`:

- The AS MUST respond with the error code `invalid_authorization_details` (per [RFC9396] Section 5) when an `ent` value is not well-formed (Section 4.3.3 step 1), or when no entitlement-bearing declared profile accepts it (Section 4.3.3 step 2).
- The AS MUST respond with the error code `invalid_authorization_details_type` (per [RFC9396] Section 5) when the agent entitlement corresponds to no profile the operator has declared — that is, an `aid` naming an undeclared profile (Section 4.3.2 step 1), this being the closest analogue to an unknown authorization-detail type.

The AS MUST respond with `invalid_request` (per [RFC8693] Section 2.2.2) when both `aid` and `ent` are present (Section 4.3.1), and when validated `entitlement_profiles` metadata cannot be obtained while the actor_token carries `aid` or `ent` (Section 4.2).

This profile defines no new error codes; it reuses [RFC9396] Section 5 and [RFC8693] Section 2.2.2 behaviour. (An earlier revision defined an `invalid_entitlement` code; it has been removed in favour of the [RFC9396] alignment.)

### 5.5. Absence of an Agent Entitlement

An actor_token carrying neither `aid` nor `ent`, or carrying an `aid` that names an entitlement-free profile, receives no agent-entitlement ceiling from this profile. Declaring `entitlement_profiles` enables an operator’s agents to opt in to a per-request entitlement constraint; it does not impose one. Deployments requiring every actor_token from an operator to carry an entitlement MUST enforce this via local AS policy.

