## 6. The `entitlement_profiles` Metadata Member

This specification defines a metadata member, `entitlement_profiles`, published in the metadata of an agent operator’s OAuth client. It declares the named profiles agents of that operator may reference via `aid`, and against which inline `ent` claims are validated.

### 6.1. Location

The member appears within the agent operator’s OAuth client metadata, wherever that metadata is published (Section 4.2): as a member of the `oauth_client` metadata in an OpenID Federation Entity Configuration; in a Client ID Metadata Document; or in [RFC7591] registered client metadata. The member is OPTIONAL. An operator with no `entitlement_profiles` declares no profiles; actor_tokens from it cannot meaningfully carry `aid` or `ent`.

### 6.2. Structure

The `entitlement_profiles` member is a JSON object. Each member key is a profile name (the string space referenced by `aid`). Each member value is a JSON object, the **profile declaration**.

A profile declaration is one of:

- **Entitlement-bearing.** It describes which fields an entitlement may contain, which are required, and the bounds the AS enforces (Section 4.3) — for example a numeric ceiling, an enumerated set of `actions`, permitted `locations`. Such a profile can be referenced by `aid` and can be the target against which an `ent` is validated.
- **Entitlement-free.** It declares the profile name with no entitlement constraint — recognising and naming an agent without bounding it (Section 3.2). An entitlement-free profile is referenced by `aid` only; it is never the target of `ent` validation (Section 4.3.3 note). It is represented as an empty object, or an object carrying only descriptive (non-constraint) members; the precise representation is deployment-defined, but the absence of constraint members (no `required`/`permitted`/`bounds` or their deployment equivalents) signals entitlement-free.

The precise schema language for profile declarations is deployment-defined in this revision; a future revision is expected to fix a normative vocabulary. Whatever the language, the AS MUST be able to mechanically decide, for any candidate `ent`, whether it conforms to and is bounded by an entitlement-bearing profile, and MUST be able to distinguish entitlement-bearing from entitlement-free profiles.

### 6.3. Example

```
"oauth_client": {
  ...
  "entitlement_profiles": {
    "payment_initiation": {
      "required": ["actions", "instructedAmount", "creditorAccount"],
      "permitted": ["actions", "instructedAmount", "creditorAccount",
                    "locations"],
      "bounds": {
        "actions": { "enum": ["initiate"] },
        "instructedAmount.currency": { "enum": ["AUD"] },
        "instructedAmount.amount": { "max": "1000.00" }
      }
    },
    "account_information": {
      "required": ["actions"],
      "permitted": ["actions", "locations"],
      "bounds": {
        "actions": { "subset_of": ["retrieve", "list"] }
      }
    },
    "concierge_recognised": {}
  }
}
```

`payment_initiation` and `account_information` are entitlement-bearing. `concierge_recognised` is entitlement-free: an actor_token with `aid: "concierge_recognised"` identifies the agent and authorises the delegation with no resource-domain entitlement ceiling from this profile.

