## Appendix A. Worked Examples

Both examples use the same agent operator (`agents.example.com`) with the `entitlement_profiles` of Section 6.3.

### A.1. Actor Token Using `aid` (Entitlement-Bearing Profile)

```json
{
  "iss": "https://agents.example.com",
  "sub": "atlas-concierge-instance-7",
  "aud": "https://as.bank.example.com",
  "iat": 1747180800,
  "exp": 1747180860,
  "jti": "5a1f4d8e-...-9c7b",
  "aid": "payment_initiation"
}
```

AS processing: actor_token validated; only `aid` present; `payment_initiation` is declared and entitlement-bearing; validated entitlement is that profile’s declared constraint; token issued bounded by the profile intersected with request and policy.

### A.2. Actor Token Using `aid` (Entitlement-Free Profile)

```json
{
  "iss": "https://agents.example.com",
  "sub": "atlas-concierge-instance-7",
  "aud": "https://as.bank.example.com",
  "iat": 1747180800,
  "exp": 1747180860,
  "jti": "5a1f4d8e-...-9c7d",
  "aid": "concierge_recognised"
}
```

AS processing: `concierge_recognised` is declared and entitlement-free; the agent is recognised and the delegation proceeds with no agent-entitlement ceiling from this profile; `scope`/`resource`/AS policy still apply (Section 5.5).

### A.3. Actor Token Using `ent` (Inline)

```json
{
  "iss": "https://agents.example.com",
  "sub": "atlas-concierge-instance-7",
  "aud": "https://as.bank.example.com",
  "iat": 1747180800,
  "exp": 1747180860,
  "jti": "5a1f4d8e-...-9c7c",
  "ent": {
    "actions": ["initiate"],
    "instructedAmount": { "currency": "AUD", "amount": "500.00" },
    "creditorAccount": { "identifier": "AU-BSB-123456-7890123" }
  }
}
```

AS processing: `ent` confirmed a well-formed JSON object; validated against declared profiles — conforms to `payment_initiation` (`actions` within enum, amount within ceiling, `creditorAccount` present, no field outside permitted); validated entitlement is the `ent` object. Had `instructedAmount.amount` been `"1500.00"`, the AS would respond `invalid_authorization_details` (no declared profile accepts it). Had `ent` been a JSON array rather than an object, the AS would respond `invalid_authorization_details` (malformed).

### A.4. Issued Access Token with Reflected `act`

```json
{
  "iss": "https://as.bank.example.com",
  "sub": "bank-customer-bdc",
  "aud": "https://api.bank.example.com",
  "iat": 1747180860,
  "exp": 1747184460,
  "scope": "payment:initiate",
  "act": {
    "iss": "https://agents.example.com",
    "sub": "atlas-concierge-instance-7",
    "aid": "payment_initiation"
  }
}
```

The resource server sees: principal `bank-customer-bdc`; current actor `atlas-concierge-instance-7` from `agents.example.com`; agent’s standing entitlement is `payment_initiation`. Per [RFC8693] Section 4.1, access-control considers principal and current actor; `aid` is identity-scoped descriptive information (Section 1.2). Reflecting `aid` rather than `ent` keeps concrete values out of the issued token (Section 8.4); a resource server enforcing on `aid` must be able to resolve the profile (Section 8.7).

